This would make it so that our dependencies have to all be explicitly resolved, not overwritten according to Maven's precedence rules.

For example, we currently have situations like this:

 * B -> proto version _x_
 * A -> proto version _y_ (let's say it is earlier)
 * A -> B

We end up with A -> proto version _y_ so now when B calls a proto version _x_ method it crashes. In this case, B needs to bundle proto or A needs to upgrade.

Dependency convergence forces one of these to be done explicitly. It will increase the number of explicit exclusions we have, but will prevent accidentally having two versions with precedence that depend on vagaries of the dep graph.

Specifically today, we have this situation between sdks/java/io/gcp and the Java dataflow runner, and users have been hit by having the wrong version of proto included.

Your correct in saying that a value may change and yet produce the same structural value. Contractually a structural value is a way for a user to provide an object which correctly implements `Object.equals` similar to Guava's EquivalenceWrapper. Since the Java SDK only is meant to rely on structural values when using Java maps and other hashcode/equals methods it should be the only thing we care to test correctly. If the user implements `Object.equals` correctly but structural value incorrectly then its likely we will not do the right thing for them since the SDK uses their type as keys in internal maps. I don't think we can do better then this for immutability testing since if we rely on other methods for checking if things are equal we won't be following the contract that matters to the SDK and that the SDK relies on.
